---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import srcImage from "../../assets/best-bass-fishing-spots-beaverton-oregon.png";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import MyH1 from "../../components/MyH1.astro";
import Bests from "../../components/Bests.astro";
---
<Layout 
title="Best bass fishing spots near Beverton, Oregon"
description="Comprehensive guide to best bass fishing hotspots – with seasonal tips, gear suggestions, and local insights."
url="https://beverton.oregonfishingforum.com/bass/best-spots/"
type="article"
site_name="Oregon Fishing Forum"
ogimage={srcImage.src}
>
    <div class="text-center">
        <MyH1 text="Best bass fishing spots near Beverton, Oregon" />
        <p class="mb-4">Comprehensive guide to best bass fishing hotspots – with seasonal tips, gear suggestions, and local insights.</p>

        <Image
            src={srcImage}
            alt="Best bass fishing spots near Beverton, Oregon"
            loading={"eager"}
            fetchpriority={"high"}
            class="rounded-xl shadow mx-auto"
            />
            <br>
    </div>

<h3>
    <strong>1. Henry Hagg Lake</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Just <strong>25 minutes from Beaverton</strong>, this large reservoir offers excellent <strong>largemouth and smallmouth bass</strong> fishing, stocked in spring and fall with trophy-size trout too 
    </li>
    <li>
        Great bank access and boat ramps—ideal for targeting coves, rock piles, and submerged timber areas
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Angler tip</strong>: Use spinnerbaits, crankbaits, jigs, and plastic worms around structure. Try mornings and evenings during warmer months.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Tualatin River</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        The river is <strong>loaded with bass</strong>, particularly largemouth, though some sections have bait/soft-plastic restrictions
    </li>
    <li>
        Popular local access includes <strong>Cook Park in Tigard</strong>, which also has a boat launch 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Recommended baits</strong>: Soft plastics under floats, spinners and jigs fished along weed edges.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Commonwealth Lake Park</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Located in Cedar Hills, this <strong>stocked neighborhood lake</strong> supports <strong>bass, bluegill, crappie</strong>, and trout
    </li>
    <li>
        It features ADA-accessible docks and picnic areas—perfect for families and casual anglers.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Try early morning cooler hours</strong> with small spinners or plastic worms along the shoreline.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>4. Progress Ridge Lake</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A deep, former quarry pond that stocks trout—and also holds bass 
    </li>
    <li>
        Features a floating fishing platform, making it accessible and engaging for beginners and kids.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Best technique</strong>: Light jigs, spoons, and plastics fished around drop-offs and underwater structure.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>5. Bethany Lake</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        A family-friendly pond stocking <strong>rainbows and warmwater species</strong>, including bass and crappie
    </li>
    <li>
        Easily accessible with paved paths; ideal for casual fishing outings.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>6. Cook Park (Tualatin River)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Noted in the ODFW guide as a top spot for <strong>largemouth bass</strong>, with a dock and boat ramp available 
    </li>
    <li>
        Fish from shore or launch a boat/kayak to target structure and weed edges.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Seasonal &amp; Tactical Summary
</h2>
<figure class="table">
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>
                    <strong>Spot</strong>
                </th>
