            <tr>
                <td>
                    <strong>Hagg Lake</strong>
                </td>
                <td>
                    Spring–Summer; low light hours
                </td>
                <td>
                    Spinnerbaits, crankbaits, jigs, rubber worms near structure
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    <strong>Tualatin River</strong>
                </td>
                <td>
                    Warm months
                </td>
                <td>
                    Plastic worms under floats, spinnerbaits near weed edges
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    <strong>Commonwealth / Bethany / Progress Lakes</strong>
                </td>
                <td>
                    Spring stocking; warm months
                </td>
                <td>
                    Light plastic worms, small spinners from shore
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>
                    <strong>Cook Park</strong>
                </td>
                <td>
                    Warm-water season
                </td>
                <td>
                    Jigs and soft plastics around docks and shoreline structure
                </td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>
</figure>
<h2>
    Pro Tips for Bass Fishing in Beaverton
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Gear up</strong> with a medium-heavy rod, 10–15 lb line, and a baitcaster or spinning setup.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Color choices</strong>: natural green/brown in clear water; bright chartreuse or black in stained conditions.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Boats &amp; Kayaks</strong>: recommended for Hagg and Progress lakes to reach deeper holding areas.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Family-friendly</strong>: Commonwealth, Bethany, Progress, and Cook Park are perfect for easy-access outings.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Know the regs</strong>: some parts of Tualatin prohibit soft plastics—check ODFW before heading out
    </li>
</ul>

